In Albany, NY, on an overcast day in June around 4 PM, the sky would likely appear gray or dull due to the thick cloud cover blocking much of the sunlight. Overcast conditions occur when the sky is covered with clouds, which diffuse and scatter sunlight, resulting in less direct light reaching the surface. This can lead to a dimmer appearance compared to a clear day. The specific shade of gray can vary depending on factors such as the thickness and type of clouds present, as well as the time of day and location. Overall, the sky would not have a vibrant color like blue or orange typically seen during clear or partly cloudy conditions.